l in the Mire of Quiet Dust and request the pacification sigils, receiving his instruction beneath ash-boughed warding cords.\",\n        \"Survive the miasma and leech-cords while memorizing the Grave-Binders’ rite without writing it, holding the steps and breaths only in bone and pulse.\",\n        \"Cut and consecrate a new set of ash-cords at a working plague altar that still remembers mercy, letting sootwater and ash mark the knots.\",\n        \"Resist or accept the Dustmother’s offered sleep and return with the cords intact, keeping memory and intent whole enough to guide the living and the newly unsettled.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Marek Sol\", \"lines\": \"The living are louder than the dead, and the frightened are loudest of all, for fear bangs on every door in the body at once. What stirs your river will stir your people, and then they will stir their own dead, not out of malice but out of misaligned love. The sigils I give are not chains; they are hands held until shaking passes, a grammar of pauses that tells a storm it can sit and breathe. You will not ink them on paper because a line on paper is a lie that pretends it does not move, and these sigils must move with breath and heartbeat. You will learn them in your marrow and in the pulse you feel in your wrist when you put two fingers there and the world agrees you are alive. Walk the fen without naming it your own, and it will teach you which silence soothes and which binds. And when you tie a knot to quiet a mouth that is only weeping, remember that mercy is not a gag but a warm hand over cold fingers until the tremor leaves.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Iriel Vask\", \"lines\": \"I have walked here once and taken the first sleep the Dustmother offers, and that first sleep tasted like a bell that forgot its clapper and rested at last. I will not pretend otherwise, because a lie told in the Mire seems to float on the water until even the frogs will not sing near it. If she comes to me in soot and gentleness again, I will bow to the kindness in it, but I will not lie down where my name cannot find me twice. Teach me to quiet what is roused without stilling it forever, to calm a startle without calling it death, and I will carry that quiet back to a city that has forgotten how to rest. My hands know gates and bearings and the sigh a promise makes when it is tuned; let them also learn the knots that keep grief from becoming a tide. And if my memory wavers in the miasma, I will steady it on the rhythm of my steps and the fourth-rib tone that has not failed me yet.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Dustmother (felt, not heard)\", \"lines\": \"Little map-reader, you carry a crease in your sleep where my fingers once smoothed you, and it whispers to me as reeds whisper to wind. Two rests and you will not wake, because the second cup is not a draught but a home where clocks forget to count and names soften like wet ash. One was mercy and silence when your heart rattled like a jar of pins; the second would be love and erasure, a soft and endless untying of knots you have not yet learned to tie. Turn your face to the wet bark and I will give you a dream with no edges, where doors do not close because there are no rooms to need them. Turn away and I will give you back your obligations, and they will scratch, but the scratches are how you know your skin belongs to you. I do not argue; I offer, as the marsh offers fog to the dawn, and what you choose will be a weather that follows you.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Marek Sol\", \"lines\": \"You are honest about your weakness, and that honesty is a lantern that keeps worse hungers at a respectful distance. That will keep you from becoming cruel with your strength, because those who forget their soft places make hard prisons with their art. Bind the recently unsettled, not the unruly wind, and remember our taboo: do not summon voices that do not consent, for even the dead dislike being dragged by their names. If your city must choose to listen, teach it to ask, and wire its listening to patience rather than to panic. Cut your cords from an altar that still remembers mercy enough to refuse a third knot when two will do, and let sootwater bless them without boiling. When the leech-cords climb, sing the fourth-rib pitch in your throat, low and steady, and they will fall away like tired thoughts. Return by dusk with the cords intact and your memory unblotted, and I will ash-mark you where the brow meets the vow so your work can meet you halfway.\"\n      ]},\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Stand Awake in the Mire\", \"text\": \"Iriel sets the Green-Shutter Lantern on a hummock and breathes with the reeds until the craving for sleep becomes a shape with edges instead of an ocean. The miasma folds and unfolds like a patient hand, and each breath is counted against the fourth-rib tone until numbers turn back into a song. The Dustmother’s cool invitation brushes the hair at the nape like dew, but the osteomancer holds to the rasp in their own voice, a reminder that living is imperfect music. Marek’s instruction becomes a cadence in the bones, and the sigils unspool as gestures remembered in joints rather than on parchment. With knife and care, Iriel harvests ash-bark in thin curls, refuses the soft bed of black moss, and knots each cord to the tempo of a heart that chooses to remain awake.\", \"outcome\": \"Clarity bites like cold water, and the cords drink that clarity until their fibers feel like intent braided with patience. The Dustmother does not sulk; she recedes like fog before noon, leaving a faint taste of rain where a kiss would have been, and the marsh hums with a quiet that is not sleep but consent. Marek studies Iriel’s eyes and nods once, seeing no frost of dream clinging to the lashes, and he marks the brow with ash that smells faintly of lime and lantern oil. The rite holds in memory like a song learned in childhood, secure enough to survive the racket of streets and council bells without a single written line. In later nights, when newly unsettled dead rattle at shutters, these cords will answer with the same awake kindness, and doors will stay on their hinges because panic never had its way.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C2\", \"title\": \"Sip the Second Cup and Tie a Tether\", \"text\": \"Iriel bites a fingertip and stains a cord-knot with a drop of living red, then loops the ash-cord around the wrist as Marek warned never to do except in extremity. The Dustmother’s presence is a cool shawl laid over shoulders, not weight but absence of ache, and the eyelids grow gentle as if taught a lullaby. Before sleep closes like a lid, Iriel hums the fourth-rib pitch and sets the lantern’s shutter to a slow pulse, an agreement between body and vow. The dream comes clear and edge-less, a place where obligations drift like lanterns on a dark canal but do not sink, and a hand made of damp night smooths down the old shard-scar to read it. The tether hums once, twice, thrice, and the marrow remembers to rise in time with the lantern, as if waking were simply another verse of the same song.\", \"outcome\": \"The second sleep lingers in the bones like a sweetness that refuses to leave the tongue, and for a few breaths after waking the frogs seem to speak in names that vanish when followed. A memory slips sideways, not lost but rearranged, and Iriel must relearn the exact angle of Marek’s first knot by feeling rather than by knowing, which deepens skill by forcing attention. The Dustmother does not take offense; she threads a breath through the cords that smells of wet bark, and the pacifications learn a softness that calms children and elders alike. Marek frowns at the wrist-knot and then lets it pass, reading the intent in the weave and the steadiness behind the gamble, and his ash-mark includes a narrow curve that warns against future bargains. The cords return intact, carrying a blessing that is half risk and half mercy, and in the nights to come they will quiet grief that no stern command could soothe.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C3\", \"title\": \"Bargain in Good Faith\", \"text\": \"Iriel kneels at the plague altar and speaks aloud a vow to use the cords first for the frightened living before the unquiet dead, promising order to Mercy rather than power to Pride. The vow includes a refusal to sell names for speed and a promise to ask permission from every threshold before crossing, even if the door swings on panic. The Dustmother gathers close to listen, a listening that cools sweat and turns the itch of miasma into the tick of a patient clock, neither kind nor cruel, simply attentive. Marek’s ash-smudged hand lays two fingers against Iriel’s pulse as witness, and the Mire’s reeds move though no wind passes, as if nodding in council. The cords are cut to the beat of the vow, each strand measuring not only length but intention, as though the altar itself weighs words the way the Loom of Names weighs chits.\", \"outcome\": \"The Dustmother accepts the bargain the way water accepts a boat, neither lifting nor drowning it, and in that acceptance the cords take on a faint sheen that stays even after drying. The vow tightens future choices, making shortcuts taste like sand, but it also clears paths in the heart where hesitation used to breed, giving courage that does not swagger. Marek inscribes the ash-mark in a pattern of three breaths and one pause, a Grave-Binder cadence that signals to wardens that this bearer has sworn mercy before mastery. In practice back in Marrowgate, the cords quiet alley panics and wake-fevers without shouting, and rumor says doors open a heartbeat sooner when they feel these knots at the latch. The bargain plants a small, green silence behind Iriel’s tongue that grows when promises are kept, and it will be noticed by those who listen for such growth in council halls and under bridges.\"\n      ],\n      \"connections\": {\"previous\": [\"M6\